<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,510,751]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
The identification of Afrotropical 
<taxonomicName box="[557,692,510,535]" class="Insecta" family="Conopidae" genus="Thecophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[557,692,510,535]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Thecophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is extremely difficult using the existing literature because the species descriptions are usually inadequate for the separation of closely related species, many of which are very similar. In most cases only females can reliably be identified. The interpretation of the Afrotropical species is summarised in the key below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,510,751]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
At present there are some 
<number box="[504,531,655,679]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="11.0">11</number>
<taxonomicName box="[540,676,654,679]" class="Insecta" family="Conopidae" genus="Thecophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[540,676,654,679]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Thecophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species recognised in the Afrotropical Region. Additional species can be expected, however, since a few of the male specimens which came to my attention might represent undescribed species.
</paragraph>
